    "body": "### Problem\n\nAs of today, and by reading the docs, I cannot say what the two examples below do.\r\n\r\nCalling the function with a local-window option and providing the `buf` parameter:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim_set_option_value('cursorline', 1, {'buf': 2})\r\n```\r\n\r\nFor this one, it appears that the current behavior is that it sets the window option for the current window if the given buffer is the current one, and otherwise for the first window showing the given buffer.\r\n\r\nThis is not intuitive nor clearly communicated at all.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCalling the function with a local-buffer option and providing the `win` parameter:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim_set_option_value('filetype', 'json', {'win': 1000})\r\n```\r\n\r\nI don't know what this does.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nJust call the above functions.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThose weird behaviors should be declared as bugs and prevented, or should be clearly expressed and documented.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.9.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, at it is lua\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 22\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nxfce4-terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nnix",
